Comment: e4. Centre opening - lets the Bishop and Queen out.
c5. The Sicilian Defense, which is one of the most commonly played openings in the world.
Nf3. The normal line of the Sicilian.
e6, deviating from the main line. This is supposed to strengthen d5 and also let the Bishop and Queen come out when needed.
d4, letting the dark-squared Bishop come out and also not blocking in the light squared Bishop.
Exchange of the pawns, letting White have a N on d4.
Recapture.
Developing a Knight. If NxN, White will have swapped off the only developed piece and after bxN Black can push into the centre with d5 and develop quickly on the queenside.
Defending the e pawn and developing a piece.
Protects against N or B to b5.
Defending the Knight and developing a piece.
An attempt to go through the middle with an attack.
Swaps off the pawn, as I preferred this line to not taking the pawn: for example ...dxe4 Nxe4 leaves two knights in the centre easily attacked.
Recaptures.
Develops the Bishop - ready to castle. Notice Black has one piece developed and White has 4.
Black now has 2 pieces developed. Both people carry on developing in the next few moves.
